      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Mark; are you objecting to the interface change, or are you asking for documentation and/or asserts on what\u0027s allowable in the keys and values?\n\nI’m doing both and neither. I’m trying not to be prescriptive, I’m just raising concerns.\n\nA const char* interface is a natural fit for an implementation that relies on NUL-terminated strings in that it’s uncontroversial and does what everyone expects without any added documentation or assertions. Without touching the implementation, a StringPiece (or any other (pointer,length) pair) or std::string interface confuses matters.\n\n\u003e As the Chrome-side plumbing uses StringPiece all around, this is already broken in that strictly speaking it necessitates copying once, to satisfy the zero-termination requirement here.\n\nRight, that’s the illustration of this exact problem.\n\n\u003e I\u0027d suggest dictating no embedded zeros by contract, and asserting on that, if that\u0027s good with you.\n\nThat should be fine.",
      "parentUuid": "570de7cd_5d77ce65",
      "revId": "3c5e871919bed22f2401e230e361b6ed8ca821be",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
